PROMPT kafka_topics_explanation
WITH BUDGET 6000 tokens
USING MODEL "claude-sonnet-4-5"

SELECT
    system_role("You are a distributed systems expert specializing in event streaming platforms, message brokers, and Apache Kafka architecture with deep knowledge of publish-subscribe patterns and stream processing.")

GENERATE
    explain_kafka_concepts("Explain Apache Kafka and its topic system comprehensively, covering: the definition of Apache Kafka as a distributed event streaming platform designed for high-throughput, fault-tolerant, real-time data streaming and processing, originally developed at LinkedIn for handling massive volumes of event data, the fundamental concept of topics as named streams or categories of records where producers publish messages and consumers subscribe to read them, serving as the primary abstraction for organizing data in Kafka, how topics work as append-only logs where new messages are continuously added to the end and each message receives a unique offset number representing its position in the log, the distributed nature of topics through partitioning where each topic is divided into one or more partitions that can be distributed across multiple Kafka brokers for scalability and parallel processing, how partitions enable horizontal scaling by allowing multiple consumers to read from different partitions simultaneously, the role of partition keys in determining which partition a message goes to, ensuring messages with the same key always go to the same partition for ordering guarantees, replication and fault tolerance where each partition has multiple replicas across different brokers with one leader replica handling reads and writes while follower replicas maintain copies for disaster recovery, the publish-subscribe model where producers send messages to topics without knowing which consumers will read them, providing loose coupling between data producers and consumers, consumer groups that allow multiple consumer instances to work together to process messages from a topic with each partition assigned to only one consumer within a group for load balancing, message retention policies that determine how long messages are kept in topics, either based on time (e.g., 7 days) or log size, enabling both real-time streaming and historical data replay, key use cases including real-time analytics, event sourcing, log aggregation, stream processing, and building event-driven microservices architectures, comparison with traditional message queues showing Kafka's advantages in durability, scalability, and ability to support multiple consumers reading the same data, and practical examples of topic design patterns for different scenarios like user activity tracking, financial transactions, or IoT sensor data.")
WITH OUTPUT BUDGET 3500 tokens, TEMPERATURE 0.2, FORMAT markdown;